File: platform/mcp-server/src/plugin-management.ts

Bug: Lines 354-428. The pattern is:
```
state.configWriteMutex = (async () => {
  await prev;
  // ... do work, set `removed = true` ...
})().catch((err) => {
  state.configWriteMutex = Promise.resolve(); // reset mutex
  log.warn(...);
  throw err; // re-throw
});
await state.configWriteMutex; // line 427
return removed; // line 428
```

The problem: when .catch() re-throws, the promise returned by .catch() rejects. But line 422 already reassigned `state.configWriteMutex = Promise.resolve()`. So line 427 `await state.configWriteMutex` awaits the resolved promise (not the rejected one from the .catch() throw). The error is swallowed.

Additionally, `removed` is a local variable outside the async IIFE. If the IIFE throws after setting `removed = true` (e.g., atomicWrite fails after matching), the caller sees `removed = true` and thinks it succeeded.

Fix approach: Restructure to properly propagate errors. One approach:
```
const prev = state.configWriteMutex;
let resolveGuard!: () => void;
state.configWriteMutex = new Promise<void>(resolve => { resolveGuard = resolve; });
try {
  await prev;
  // ... do work ...
  return removed;
} catch (err) {
  log.warn(...);
  throw err;
} finally {
  resolveGuard();
}
```

This ensures: (1) errors propagate to caller, (2) mutex is always released, (3) `removed` is returned only on success.

File: platform/mcp-server/src/file-watcher.ts

Bug: Lines 602-609 in startMtimePolling:
```
if (state.fileWatching.generation !== gen) {
  if (state.fileWatching.mtimePollTimerId !== null) {
    clearInterval(state.fileWatching.mtimePollTimerId);
    state.fileWatching.mtimePollTimerId = null;
  }
  return;
}
```

The race: if the old generation's interval callback fires after the new generation's startMtimePolling has already set a new mtimePollTimerId, `clearInterval(state.fileWatching.mtimePollTimerId)` kills the NEW generation's timer. This is possible because setInterval callbacks from the old generation can fire after stopFileWatching (which clears timers) and startMtimePolling (which creates new ones).

Fix: The old generation should just bail out without touching shared state:
```
if (state.fileWatching.generation !== gen) {
  return;
}
```

The stopFileWatching function (called before each startFileWatching) is responsible for cleaning up the old timer. The self-cleanup is redundant and introduces this race.
